Aristotle believed that all the matter in the universe was made up of four basic elements \endash  earth, air, fire, and water.\par
These elements were acted on by two forces: gravity, the tendency for earth and water to sink, and levity, the tendency\par
for air and fire to rise. This division of the contents of the universe into matter and forces is still used today. Aristotle\par
believed that matter was continuous, that is, one could divide a piece of matter into smaller and smaller bits without any\par
limit: one never came up against a grain of matter that could not be divided further. A few Greeks, however, such as\par
Democritus, held that matter was inherently grainy and that everything was made up of large numbers of various different\par
kinds of atoms. (The word atom means \ldblquote indivisible\rdblquote  in Greek.) For centuries the argument continued without any real\par
evidence on either side, but in 1803 the British chemist and physicist John Dalton pointed out that the fact that chemical\par
compounds always combined in certain proportions could be explained by the grouping together of atoms to form units\par
called molecules. However, the argument between the two schools of thought was not finally settled in favor of the\par
atomists until the early years of this century. One of the important pieces of physical evidence was provided by Einstein.\par
In a paper written in 1905, a few weeks before the famous paper on special relativity, Einstein pointed out that what was\par
called Brownian motion \endash  the irregular, random motion of small particles of dust suspended in a liquid \endash  could be\par
explained as the effect of atoms of the liquid colliding with the dust particles.\par
By this time there were already suspicions that these atoms were not, after all, indivisible. Several years previously a\par
fellow of Trinity College, Cambridge, J. J. Thomson, had demonstrated the existence of a particle of matter, called the\par
electron, that had a mass less than one thousandth of that of the lightest atom. He used a setup rather like a modern TV\par
picture tube: a red-hot metal filament gave off the electrons, and because these have a negative electric charge, an\par
electric field could be used to accelerate them toward a phosphor-coated screen. When they hit the screen, flashes of\par
light were generated. Soon it was realized that these electrons must be coming from within the atoms themselves, and in\par
1911 the New Zealand physicist Ernest Rutherford finally showed that the atoms of matter do have internal structure:\par
they are made up of an extremely tiny, positively charged nucleus, around which a number of electrons orbit. He deduced\par
this by analyzing the way in which alpha-particles, which are positively charged particles given off by radioactive atoms,\par
are deflected when they collide with atoms.\par
