Our present ideas about the motion of bodies date back to Galileo and Newton. Before them people believed\par
Aristotle, who said that the natural state of a body was to be at rest and that it moved only if driven by a force or\par
impulse. It followed that a heavy body should fall faster than a light one, because it would have a greater pull\par
toward the earth.\par
The Aristotelian tradition also held that one could work out all the laws that govern the universe by pure\par
thought: it was not necessary to check by observation. So no one until Galileo bothered to see whether bodies\par
of different weight did in fact fall at different speeds. It is said that Galileo demonstrated that Aristotle\rquote s belief\par
was false by dropping weights from the leaning tower of Pisa. The story is almost certainly untrue, but Galileo\par
did do something equivalent: he rolled balls of different weights down a smooth slope. The situation is similar to\par
that of heavy bodies falling vertically, but it is easier to observe because the Speeds are smaller. Galileo\rquote s\par
measurements indicated that each body increased its speed at the same rate, no matter what its weight. For\par
example, if you let go of a ball on a slope that drops by one meter for every ten meters you go along, the ball\par
will be traveling down the slope at a speed of about one meter per second after one second, two meters per\par
second after two seconds, and so on, however heavy the ball. Of course a lead weight would fall faster than a\par
feather, but that is only because a feather is slowed down by air resistance. If one drops two bodies that don\rquote t\par
have much air resistance, such as two different lead weights, they fall at the same rate. On the moon, where\par
there is no air to slow things down, the astronaut David R. Scott performed the feather and lead weight\par
experiment and found that indeed they did hit the ground at the same time.\par
