A well-known scientist (some say it was Bertrand Russell) once gave a public lecture on astronomy. He\par
described how the earth orbits around the sun and how the sun, in turn, orbits around the center of a vast\par
collection of stars called our galaxy. At the end of the lecture, a little old lady at the back of the room got up and\par
said: \ldblquote What you have told us is rubbish. The world is really a flat plate supported on the back of a giant\par
tortoise.\rdblquote  The scientist gave a superior smile before replying, \ldblquote What is the tortoise standing on.\rdblquote  \ldblquote You\rquote re very\par
clever, young man, very clever,\rdblquote  said the old lady. \ldblquote But it\rquote s turtles all the way down!\rdblquote\par
Most people would find the picture of our universe as an infinite tower of tortoises rather ridiculous, but why do\par
we think we know better? What do we know about the universe, and how do we know it? Where did the\par
universe come from, and where is it going? Did the universe have a beginning, and if so, what happened before\par
then? What is the nature of time? Will it ever come to an end? Can we go back in time? Recent breakthroughs\par
in physics, made possible in part by fantastic new technologies, suggest answers to some of these\par
longstanding questions. Someday these answers may seem as obvious to us as the earth orbiting the sun \endash  or\par
perhaps as ridiculous as a tower of tortoises. Only time (whatever that may be) will tell.\par
As long ago as 340 BC the Greek philosopher Aristotle, in his book On the Heavens, was able to put forward\par
two good arguments for believing that the earth was a round sphere rather than a Hat plate. First, he realized\par
that eclipses of the moon were caused by the earth coming between the sun and the moon. The earth\rquote s\par
shadow on the moon was always round, which would be true only if the earth was spherical. If the earth had\par
been a flat disk, the shadow would have been elongated and elliptical, unless the eclipse always occurred at a\par
time when the sun was directly under the center of the disk. Second, the Greeks knew from their travels that\par
the North Star appeared lower in the sky when viewed in the south than it did in more northerly regions. (Since\par
the North Star lies over the North Pole, it appears to be directly above an observer at the North Pole, but to\par
someone looking from the equator, it appears to lie just at the horizon. From the difference in the apparent\par
position of the North Star in Egypt and Greece, Aristotle even quoted an estimate that the distance around the\par
earth was 400,000 stadia. It is not known exactly what length a stadium was, but it may have been about 200\par
yards, which would make Aristotle\rquote s estimate about twice the currently accepted figure. The Greeks even had a\par
third argument that the earth must be round, for why else does one first see the sails of a ship coming over the\par
horizon, and only later see the hull?\par
